  "text": "Django's MIDDLEWARE setting processing is implemented through a sophisticated stack construction and request/response handling mechanism:\n\n## Middleware Stack Construction\n\nThe core middleware loading happens in `django/core/handlers/base.py:27-104` in the `BaseHandler.load_middleware()` method. This method:\n\n1. **Loads middleware in reverse order** (line 41: `for middleware_path in reversed(settings.MIDDLEWARE)`): The MIDDLEWARE setting list is reversed during loading to create a nested callable structure where each middleware wraps the next one. This creates an \"onion\" pattern where:\n   - The innermost callable is either `_get_response` (sync) or `_get_response_async` (async)\n   - Each middleware wraps around the next middleware in the chain\n   - The outermost middleware is the first one in the MIDDLEWARE list\n\n2. **Imports middleware classes** (line 42): Each middleware path string is imported using `import_string(middleware_path)`\n\n3. **Handles async/sync compatibility** (lines 43-53): Checks `sync_capable` and `async_capable` attributes to determine if middleware supports the current mode (sync or async)\n\n4. **Adapts handler modes** (lines 56-62): Uses `adapt_method_mode()` to wrap sync middleware with `sync_to_async()` or async middleware with `async_to_sync()` as needed\n\n5. **Instantiates middleware** (line 63): Creates middleware instances by calling the middleware class with the adapted handler: `mw_instance = middleware(adapted_handler)`\n\n6. **Handles MiddlewareNotUsed exception** (lines 64-70): If a middleware raises `MiddlewareNotUsed` in its `__init__()`, it's excluded from the chain\n\n7. **Collects special middleware methods** (lines 79-95): Extracts `process_view`, `process_template_response`, and `process_exception` methods and stores them in separate lists for ordered execution\n\n8. **Wraps each handler with exception conversion** (line 97): Each middleware is wrapped with `convert_exception_to_response()` to ensure exceptions are converted to HTTP responses\n\n## Request/Response Processing Order\n\nThe \"onion\" structure created by the reversed loading order means:\n\n**Request phase (top-down)**: Middleware process requests in the order they appear in MIDDLEWARE because they're nested in reverse:\n- Request enters the outermost middleware first\n- Each middleware calls `get_response()` to pass control to the next layer\n- Finally reaches the view\n\n**Response phase (bottom-up)**: Responses pass back through the same middleware layers:\n- After view execution, responses flow back through each middleware's post-processing code\n- Only middleware that saw the request will see the response\n- If a middleware short-circuits by returning a response without calling `get_response()`, inner layers never see the request or response\n\n## Middleware Interface\n\nThe `MiddlewareMixin` class in `django/utils/deprecation.py:275-331` provides the standard middleware interface:\n\n1. **`__init__(get_response)`** (line 279): Accepts the next handler in the chain\n\n2. **`__call__(request)`** (line 302-312) for sync requests:\n   - Calls `process_request()` if defined\n   - Calls `get_response(request)` to get the response from inner middleware/view\n   - Calls `process_response(request, response)` if defined\n   - Returns the response\n\n3. **`__acall__(request)`** (line 314-331) for async requests:\n   - Same pattern but using `await` with `sync_to_async()` wrappers for sync middleware methods\n\n## Special Middleware Methods\n\nBeyond the basic request/response pattern, middleware can implement:\n\n1. **`process_view(request, view_func, view_args, view_kwargs)`**: Called just before the view, executes in the order defined in MIDDLEWARE (lines 79-83 of base.py). Can short-circuit by returning a response.\n\n2. **`process_exception(request, exception)`**: Called when the view raises an exception. Executes in reverse order (lines 90-95). Stored in `_exception_middleware` list.\n\n3. **`process_template_response(request, response)`**: Called after the view if response has a `render()` method. Executes in reverse order (lines 84-89). Stored in `_template_response_middleware` list.\n\n## Exception Handling in Middleware\n\nThe `convert_exception_to_response()` function in `django/core/handlers/exception.py:25-61` wraps every middleware and handler:\n\n- Automatically converts all exceptions to appropriate HTTP responses\n- Ensures exceptions raised within middleware don't crash the application\n- Allows the next middleware in the chain to see the error response instead of an exception\n- This is a key difference from the old MIDDLEWARE_CLASSES system\n\n## WSGI vs MIDDLEWARE Processing\n\nThe comparison between old `MIDDLEWARE_CLASSES` and new `MIDDLEWARE` setting reveals important architectural differences documented in `docs/topics/http/middleware.txt:427-456`:\n\n**Old MIDDLEWARE_CLASSES (deprecated)**:\n- process_request methods called top-down\n- process_response methods ALWAYS called bottom-up, even if an earlier middleware short-circuited\n- process_exception applies to exceptions from other middleware's process_request\n- If process_response raises an exception, all earlier process_response methods are skipped\n\n**New MIDDLEWARE setting**:\n- Implements an \"onion\" model where response handling mirrors request handling\n- Only middleware that saw the request will see the response\n- Short-circuiting is properly supported - inner middleware don't execute if outer middleware returns a response\n- Exceptions from middleware are converted to responses, and subsequent middleware see the response, not the exception\n- process_exception applies only to view exceptions, not middleware exceptions\n- More predictable and consistent behavior\n\n## Handler Integration\n\nWSGIHandler (`django/core/handlers/wsgi.py:113-144`) and ASGIHandler (`django/core/handlers/asgi.py:143-152`) both:\n1. Inherit from BaseHandler\n2. Call `load_middleware()` in their `__init__()` to construct the middleware chain\n3. Use `self._middleware_chain` as their entry point to process requests\n\nThis unified architecture means the same middleware stack is used for both WSGI and ASGI applications, with automatic adaptation for sync/async compatibility."
